<Base title="About" description="Oxford LLMs is an independent research lab focused on how social scientists can use language models.">
  <div class="container container--content">

    <div class="page-header">
      <p class="section-label">About</p>
      <h1 class="page-header__title">Oxford LLMs</h1>
      <p class="page-header__desc">
        An independent research lab focused on how social scientists can use language models. Founded in 2023 at the University of Oxford.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <h2>What We Do</h2>
      <p>
        Large language models are transforming social science research, but using them well
        requires specialised training that bridges machine learning and the social sciences.
        Oxford LLMs addresses this gap through three activities:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Research.</strong> We develop new methods for applying LLMs to social science problems,
        with a focus on synthetic data generation, opinion prediction, and model evaluation.
        Some of this work is ongoing; other projects are completed and are being peer-reviewed.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Teaching.</strong> We deliver courses on LLMs for social scientists at Oxford,
        Sciences Po Paris, and the European University Institute in Florence.
        All materials are open-source.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Community.</strong> Our annual summer school, now in its third year, brings together
        early-career researchers for an intensive week of lectures, coding, and collaborative
        research. Past participants have gone on to co-author publications.
      </p>

      <h2>Team</h2>
      <p>
        Oxford LLMs is led by <strong>Maksim Zubok</strong> (DPhil candidate, DPIR, Nuffield College)
        and <strong>Ilya Boytsov</strong> (NLP Lead, Wayfair).
        <strong>Rachel Bernhard</strong> (Associate Professor, Nuffield College) was co-organiser in 2025,
        and <strong>Humeyra Biricik</strong> (doctoral candidate, Pembroke College) in 2024.
      </p>

      <h2>Partners & Supporters</h2>
      <p>
        Oxford LLMs operates as an independent research lab. Our work has been supported by
        academic institutions and industry partners who share our commitment to open research
        and education.
      </p>

